"1028","1039":"1039","1137":"1137","1004":"1004","1056":"1056","1067":"1067","1011":"1011","1076":"1076","1087":"1087","1109":"1109","La Fère, Aisne, Hauts-de-France, France":"La Fère, Aisne, Hauts-de-France, France","La Fère, Aisne, Picardie, France":"La Fère, Aisne, Picardie, France","Boves, Amiens, Somme, Picardie, France":"Boves, Amiens, Somme, Picardie, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"DE","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"LA","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Hung, Cuong, Anh, Thanh, Ha, Hoang, Tuan, Chau, Hao, Hien, Hoa, Hue, Nam, Phong, Sinh, Tuong, Min, Tam, Tanh, Thai, Tham, Tinh, Yeong.  Chinese Hong, Hang, Sang, Tong, Chan, Chi, Hwa Ja, Hyung, Kam, Ki Bong, Kin, Man.","Vietnamese: from the Chinese surname 羅, see   Luo   1.","Vietnamese (<b>Lã</b>): from the Chinese surname 呂, see   Lu   6 and 3 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Luo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Jian, Yi, Ping, Yong, Zhen, Feng, Hong, Ming, Jin, Bin, Chen, Hai, Lan, Min, Huan, Hung, Shen, Tian.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 羅, meaning ‘net for catching birds’ or ‘to collect’ in Chinese: (i) from Luo (羅), the name of an ancient state (located in present-day Hubei province). After it was annexed by the state of Chu during the early Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ), people from the state migrated southwards and adopted Luo (羅) as their surname. (ii) from the Po Duo Luo (破多羅) and Chi Luo (叱羅) families from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China, who changed their original surnames to 羅 during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iii) from the personal name Hu Se Luo (斛瑟羅), leader of an ancient Turkic tribe who are believed to have migrated to China during the Tang dynasty (618–907  AD ). His descendants inherited his name Hu Se Luo (斛瑟羅) as their surname and shortened it to 羅 during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iv) from the name of one of the seven families from the Bandun Man, an ethnic group residing in ancient southwestern China (located mainly in present-day Sichuan province)."]}]},{"name":"FERE","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Bartolo, Croce, Dante, Domenico, Giorgio, Luigi, Pietro, Salvatore, Vincenzo, Vito.  French/Haitian Guerline, Jean Marie.","Italian: from the female personal name <i>Fede</i>, from Latin <i>fides</i> ‘faith’.","Italian: from a short form of the personal name   Federico  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Federico","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Domenic, Antonio, Guerino, Armando, Salvatore, Domenico, Gino, Mario, Nino, Sal, Carmine, Guido, Alfredo, Angelo, Benito, Carmela.  Spanish Jose, Ruben, Carlos, Jesus, Rosario, Enrique, Francisco, Juan.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Federico</i>, of ancient Germanic origin (see   Friedrich  ). Compare   Federick   and   Frederico  ."]},{"name":"Di Fede","meanings":["Italian (Sicily): patronymic or metronymic from the male or female personal name   Fede  ."]}]},{"name":"Nocher","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: topographic name denoting someone who lived in a rocky place, from <i>rocher</i> ‘rock, crag, boulder’, or a habitational name from a place called Rocher. Compare   Durocher  .","Altered form of French   Desrochers  .","History: Pierre Desrochers/Rocher from Saint-Macoux in Vienne, France, married Suzanne Rabouin in Batiscan, QC, in 1696."],"variants":[{"name":"Rocheleau","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Armand, Alphonse, Andre, Normand, Aurore, Cecile, Elphege, Emile, Fernand, Gilles, Mathieu.","Altered form of French <b>Rochereau</b>: topographic name from a diminutive of <i>rocher</i> ‘rock, crag, boulder’ (see   Rocher  ), or a habitational name from (Le) Rochereau, the name of several places in the western part of France. Compare   Rushlow  ."]},{"name":"Rochon","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Andre, Aurele, Gaston, Michel, Yves, Adrien, Antoine, Fernande, Gaetan, Germain, Gilles.","Altered form of French <b>Rocheron</b>: topographic name from a diminutive of <i>rocher</i> ‘rock, crag, boulder’ (see   Rocher  ), or a habitational name from Le Rocheron, the name of two places in Indre-et-Loire.","French: diminutive of   Roche   ‘rock’."]},{"name":"Durocher","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Fernand, Gilles, Marcel, Normand, Alain, Antoine, Armand, Bibiane, Emile, Emilien, Gaetan.","French: topographic name from <i>rocher</i> ‘rock, crag, boulder’, with fused preposition and definite article <i>du</i> ‘from the’, denoting someone who lived in a rocky place; or a habitational name for someone from Le Rocher, the name of several places in various parts of France. Compare   Derusha   and   Rocher  .","Altered form of French   Desrochers  , a cognate of 1 above."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Nocher DE LA FERE was born in 1028, in Boves, Amiens, Somme, Picardie, France, his father, Nocher DE LA FERE, was 24 and his mother, Berthilde DE THOUROTTE, was 17. He had at least 2 daughters with Gertrude De Coucy."},"et":{"1028–":"1028–Surnud","